Afrikaners make up approximately 58% of South Africa's white population, based on language used in the home. English speakers - an ethnically diverse group - account for closer to 37%.<ref name="zastudy"/> As in [[Canada]] or the [[United States]], most modern European immigrants elect to learn English and are likelier to identify with those descended from British colonials of the nineteenth century.<ref name="roskinstudies">{{cite book|last=Roskin|first=Roskin|title=Countries and concepts: an introduction to comparative politics|pages=343–373}}</ref>  Aside from coastal pockets in the [[Eastern Cape]] and [[KwaZulu-Natal]] they remain heavily outnumbered by those of Afrikaans origin.<ref name="statssa2001">{{cite web|url=http://www.statssa.gov.za/timeseriesdata/pxweb2006/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=Language%20by%20province&ti=Table%3A+Census+2001+by+province%2C+language%2C+population+group+and++gender.&path=../Database/South%20Africa/Population%20Census/Census%202001%20-%20NEW%20Demarcation%20boundaries%20as%20at%209%20December%202005/Provincial%20level%20-%20Persons/&lang=1 |title=Table: Census 2001 by province, language, population group and gender. |work=Census 2001 |publisher=Statistics South Africa |accessdate=18 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061130131334/http://www.statssa.gov.za/timeseriesdata/pxweb2006/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=Language%20by%20province&ti=Table%3A+Census+2001+by+province%2C+language%2C+population+group+and++gender.&path=..%2FDatabase%2FSouth%20Africa%2FPopulation%20Census%2FCensus%202001%20-%20NEW%20Demarcation%20boundaries%20as%20at%209%20December%202005%2FProvincial%20level%20-%20Persons%2F&lang=1 |archivedate=30 November 2006 }}</ref>

