'''Amaryllis Collymore''' (1745–1828) was an [[Afro-Barbadian]] slave who gained her freedom from her relationship with a white man. The couple had eleven children and she successfully ran a plantation allowing her to acquire numerous other properties, to become the wealthiest free black woman in the colony at the time of her death.

==Early life==
Amaryllis Renn Phillips was born into slavery in 1745{{#tag:ref|If her tombstone is correct that she was 78 years old at her death, she may have been born in 1750; however, as the date of 1745 is given by Dr. Karl Watson, the president of the Barbados National Trust, that date was used.{{sfn|Watson|2014|pp=244, 249}}|group="Notes"}} on [[Barbados]], during British colonial rule{{sfn|Gafoor|2010}} where records indicate she was a mulatto.{{sfn|Sanders|1984|p=240}}{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}} She was purchased by Robert Collmore in 1780, from Rebecca Phillips, a free coloured hotelier,{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}}{{sfn|Paugh|2017|p=271}} along with her five mulatto children,{{sfn|Paugh|2017|p=271}} four of whom were Robert's children.{{sfn|Welch|1999}} In 1784, Robert arranged their manumission by selling her and the children to a friend, James Scuffield.{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}}{{sfn|Welch|1999}} Selling a slave to a trusted third-party to avoid high manumission fees was a common practice during the period in Barbados.{{sfn|Candlin|Pybus|2015|p=43}}

Robert acquired ''Lightfoots'', a 42-acre sugar plantation with its 44 slaves, to provide for her and the children.{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}} Collymore expanded the estate to over a hundred acres{{sfn|Candlin|Pybus|2015|p=39}} and was able to buy seven properties throughout [[Bridgetown]], on Canary Street, High Street and James Street, which she rented out.{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}}{{sfn|''Nation News''|2015}} She also ran a successful shop.{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}} By 1805, Collymore owned another property, on Roebuck Street, which she sold for £800.{{sfn|Welch|1999}} She and her daughter, Katherine Anne Collymore, were the recipients of a bequest from Renn Phillips in his 1809 will.{{sfn|''The Journal of the Barbados Museum and Historical Society''|2000|p=54-55}} 

In 1824, when Robert died, he bequeathed she and her eleven children, full title to ''Lightfoots'' and the slaves working on the plantation.{{sfn|Welch|1999}} Among her children, besides Katherine were Frances Lasley, Margaret Jane, and Robert (baptized 18 February 1792),{{sfn|Sanders|1984|p=217}} Thomazin Ashby (baptized 6 June 1795),{{sfn|Sanders|1984|p=228}}, Elizabeth Clarke (baptized 13 June  1798),{{sfn|Sanders|1984|p=240}}, Samuel Francis Collymore, Jackson Brown Collymore{{sfn|Handler|2009|p=121}} and Renn Phillips Collymore, who would become the great-great grandfather of [[Frank Collymore]].{{sfn|Gafoor|2010}} Collymore's will, dated 1826{{sfn|Welch|1999}} (or 1829 but which was probably the date the estate was probated),{{sfn|Handler|2009|p=121}} left her estate, worth over £10,000 to relatives. She devised a home in Bridgetown and a plantation known as Haggat Hall, and 67 slaves, as well as silver and personal property.{{sfn|Welch|1999}} At the time of her death she was "the richest free woman of color in pre-emancipation Barbados".{{sfn|Candlin|Pybus|2015|p=39}}

==Death and legacy==
Collymore died on 16 December 1828 and was buried in the St. Mary's Churchyard in [[Bridgetown]].{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}}{{sfn|''Nation News''|2015}} The house that Collymore and her children occupied is now the Morningside Building, and houses the Arts Department of the [[Barbados Community College]].{{sfn|Watson|2014|p=249}} 

