{{about|the Royal Academician|his son, also an artist|Charles Catton the younger}} {{Infobox artist | name = Charles Catton | image = Charles Catton, by Charles Catton (1728-1798).jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Self-portrait (1769) | birth_name = | birth_date = 1728 | birth_place = [[Norwich]], Norfolk | death_date = {{Death date|df=yes|1798|08|28}} | death_place = [[New Road (London)|New Road]], London | nationality = British | spouse = | field = Oil painting, Landscape painting | training = | movement = founding member of the [[Royal Academy]] | works = | patrons = | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = | elected = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> }} '''Charles Catton''' [[Royal Academy|RA]] (1728 in [[Norwich]] – 28 August 1798, in [[London]]),<ref>[http://www.racollection.org.uk/ixbin/indexplus?_IXACTION_=file&_IXFILE_=templates/full/person.html&_IXTRAIL_=Academicians&person=5564 Charles Catton, the Elder, R.A.] (Royal Academy, London).</ref> sometimes referred to as '''Charles Catton the elder''', was a notable English [[coach painter]], [[Landscape painting|landscape]], animal and figure painter of the late 18th century, and one of the founder members of the [[Royal Academy]].
==Life and work== Catton was born in [[Norwich]], Norfolk, in 1728, and said to be one of 35 children that his father had from his two marriages.<ref name=general>{{cite book|page=1096|volume=3|title=A General History of the County of Norfolk|publisher=John Stacy|author=[[John Chambers (topographer)|John Chambers]]|location=Norwich|year=1829|url=}}</ref> He was apprenticed to a London coach painter,{{sfn|Stephen|1887}} or, according to some sources, a carpenter by the name of Maxwell,<ref name=general/> and studied drawing at the [[St. Martin's Lane Academy]]. He was mainly known as a landscape and animal painter, but also had a good knowledge of the figure, and a talent for humorous design. In 1781, he published an etching called ''The Margate Packet''.{{sfn|Stephen|1887}}
He became a member of the [[Society of Artists of Great Britain|Society of Artists]], and exhibited various pictures in its galleries in 1760–4. He was outstanding as a coach painter, producing ornamental panels for carriages, floral embellishments, and heraldic devices to the highest quality, eventually becoming coach-painter to [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]].{{sfn|Stephen|1887}} [[File:Wappen Duke of Devonshire.png|thumbnail|left|Duke of Devonshire arms]] He was a founding member of the [[Royal Academy]], and, in 1784, was master of the [[Worshipful Company of Painter-Stainers]]. He exhibited at the Academy from its foundation until the year of his death. The works he showed were usually landscapes, but occasionally subject and animal paintings, his last exhibits there being ''Jupiter and Leda'' and ''Child at play''. He painted an [[altarpiece]], ''The Angel delivering St. Peter'', for the church of [[St Peter Mancroft]] in Norwich.{{sfn|Stephen|1887}}
He retired from painting some years before his death. He died at his house in Judd Place, [[New Road (London)|New Road]], London, on 28 August 1798, and was buried in Bloomsbury cemetery.{{sfn|Stephen|1887}}<ref name="Gate">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=74268 Nos 3 and 4 Gate Street] (British History Online).</ref>
[[File:Arms of the Baroness Hamilton of Hameldon.png|thumb|Arms of the Baroness Hamilton of Hameldon, 1790]] His son, [[Charles Catton the younger]] (1756–1819), who was listed in Royal Academy catalogues as living at his father's house in Gate Street, gained a reputation as a scene-painter and topographical draughtsman.{{sfn|Stephen|1887}}<ref name="Gate" /> He emigrated to the United States.<ref name=general/> Among Catton's pupils was [[John Durand (painter)|John Durand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidwebbfowler.com/2012/12/an-18th-century-portrait-artist.html|title=COLONIAL AMERICAN DIGRESSIONS|author=David Webb Fowler|work=davidwebbfowler.com|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>
